===Public Key Format===

When CHECKSIG opcodes pop a non-empty pubkey from the stack, the verifier assumes the pubkey byte vector has the following structure:

<pre>
flag || pubkey
</pre>

… where <code>flag</code> is a byte corresponding to a standardized signature verification algorithm flag.

Two verification algorithm flags are defined in this BIP:

* <code>0x01</code>: SHRINCS.
* <code>0x02</code>: BIP340<ref>SHRINCS uses flag <code>0x01</code> while BIP340 uses flag <code>0x02</code> to avoid ambiguity when pubkeys are encoded with their algorithm flags. Because both BIP340 and SHRINCS public keys are 32 bytes long, using <code>0x02</code> for SHRINCS might lead to confusion: A user given a public key <code>0x02 || <32-byte-string></code> might think it is a compressed secp256k1 point, and not a SHRINCS key. By using <code>0x02</code> for a BIP340 pubkey, the key appears the same as it would if we took the full lifted secp256k1 curve point and encoded it with the standard compressed point encoding format.</ref>.

Any pubkey which uses an unidentified algorithm flag prefix is essentially an “anyone-can-spend” public key, because verifiers will auto-succeed when they validate signatures against that key. This allows future BIPs to define new verification algorithms.

We now define the signature verification algorithms for these two flags.


===SHRINCS===

A SHRINCS public key is a 32-byte value constructed as:
<pre>
PK = PK.seed || PK.root
</pre>

* <code>PK.seed</code> is a domain separator, used in all hash operations while producing the signature
* <code>PK.root</code> is a root commitment to both stateful and stateless public keys: <code>PK.root = Tw(PK.seed, ADRS, PK.sf || PK.sl)</code>. <code>Tw(.)</code> is a hash function with addressing.

